const LO_ANSWERS = {"31_1": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Dr. Blavo opens by deliberately downscoping the microbiology — \"we've given enough talks on those organisms\" — so the move he wants from you is not a memorized list but a pattern. Every organism collapses into one of three stool behaviors: inflammatory (EHEC, Shigella, Salmonella, Campylobacter), secretory (ETEC, Vibrio cholerae), and osmotic (rotavirus, norovirus, EPEC, Giardia). Once you know the pattern, the workup and the fluids follow — so learn the buckets, not the encyclopedia.", "why": "E. coli O157:H7 — it causes HUS, and unlike the rest it is made worse by antibiotics, so the stakes of recognizing it are highest."}, "31_2": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. For diarrhea, the history is the diagnostic test — Blavo's whole \"rote-to-rationale\" message is that you ask each question for a reason. The single most useful question is the character of the stool: loose, watery, mucoid, bloody, oily, or foul-smelling. Each adjective points somewhere.", "why": "Blood/leukocytes (inflammatory), stool volume (voluminous = secretory), and fat/odor or response to fasting (osmotic/malabsorptive) sort almost every case."}, "31_3": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. There is no rigid formal classification, but the working schema gastroenterologists carry — and the one that organizes your whole differential — is inflammatory vs non-inflammatory, with non-inflammatory splitting into secretory and osmotic. The classification is the differential diagnosis.", "why": "Secretory — an enterotoxin is actively driving secretion, so the lumen stays wet even without ingested solute; an osmotic diarrhea would have slowed or stopped with fasting."}, "31_4": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Most diarrhea is mild, self-limited, and needs no workup at all — observation, fluids, and anticipatory guidance. You investigate only when a red flag raises the stakes: moderate/severe dehydration, an ill child or elderly patient, bloody or voluminous stool, duration >48 h, high fever, severe abdominal pain, recent antibiotics, or an immunocompromised host.", "why": "You choose the single study that confirms a named hypothesis (the red-flag pattern points to it), rather than ordering a broad panel and hoping something turns up."}, "31_5": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Management is mostly rehydration, because most infectious diarrhea is self-limited — the body heals itself if you keep it in a workable fluid and electrolyte state. Blavo's childhood memory of a cholera outbreak in Ghana, and his later cholera intervention in Haiti, anchor the stakes: secretory losses can kill through dehydration even when the patient doesn't look classically \"septic.\" Oral rehydration is first-line.", "why": "Glucose drives sodium-coupled absorption (SGLT1) so water is reabsorbed even while the gut secretes; Coca-Cola's glucose-to-sodium ratio is backwards and hyperosmolar, so it pulls water into the lumen instead."}, "33_1": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Endoscopy for a GI bleed turns on two questions: is the patient hemodynamically stable or unstable, and where is the source. Unstable patients (hypotensive, tachycardic, syncope) get volume and, if exsanguinating, unmatched blood — you resuscitate before you scope.", "why": "A fast upper bleed (e.g., duodenal ulcer) presents as maroon stool from below, and unlike most lower sources you can actually stop it endoscopically — so the top is scoped first."}, "33_2": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Beyond the standard EGD and colonoscopy, three scopes are each defined by what they can do. The trick is to tag each one diagnostic, therapeutic, or both.", "why": "EUS — it stages and biopsies the mass through the gastric wall, assesses vascular involvement and nodes in one step; percutaneous biopsy risks tract seeding and undersampling."}, "33_3": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Upper endoscopy (EGD) sees from the oropharynx to the second portion of the duodenum. The biggest indication is GERD — and the reason to scope reflux is to look for Barrett's esophagus, a silent change in the lining.", "why": "Whether liquids get stuck too: solids-only points to a structural narrowing; solids-and-liquids points to a motility disorder (work it up with barium first)."}, "33_4": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Colonoscopy diagnoses the colorectal differential and removes polyps, but for bleeding its therapeutic reach is limited. The high-yield separations are the diverticular pair and the IBD patterns.", "why": "Diverticulosis — acute, painless, significant hematochezia over 50 that self-limits ~80% of the time; endoscopic therapy for lower bleeds is limited, so management is largely supportive after excluding an upper source."}, "33_5": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Indications run through the other LOs; the complications and contraindications are the testable headlines. ERCP is the most dangerous procedure gastroenterologists perform, with an overall complication rate around 10%. Its signature complication is post-ERCP pancreatitis — you are working at the tiny opening where the bile and pancreatic ducts meet, so even a flawless operator can inflame the pancreas.", "why": "ERCP — about a 10% complication rate, and its signature complication is post-ERCP pancreatitis from manipulating the shared bile/pancreatic-duct opening."}, "33_6": {"answer": "OVERVIEW. Schneider calls screening his primary responsibility — and the single highest-yield block. The logic is the adenoma-to-carcinoma sequence: precancerous adenomatous polyps become cancer over roughly a decade, so we scope to find and remove them.", "why": "Colonoscopy is offered FIRST and is the only test that also prevents cancer by removing polyps; a stool test (annual FIT) is for patients who decline colonoscopy — it detects cancer but doesn't prevent it, and Cologuard is not equivalent."}};
