const LECTURE_CONTENT = {"31": {"prof": "Cyril Blavo, D.O.", "tldr": "Acute infectious diarrhea is usually self-limited — your job is to classify it (inflammatory vs secretory vs osmotic) and replace fluid and electrolytes, orally first and IV only when oral fails.", "mustKnows": ["Classify before you treat. Split every case into inflammatory (blood + fecal leukocytes + fever; EHEC, Shigella, Salmonella, Campylobacter) vs non-inflammatory, then non-inflammatory into secretory (voluminous watery, ETEC/cholera) and osmotic (smaller volume; rotavirus, Giardia, EPEC). The bucket drives the workup and the fluids.", "Secretory diarrhea dehydrates fast. Secretory means an enterotoxin drives active secretion — voluminous watery non-bloody stools that persist even with fasting. ETEC (traveler's) and Vibrio cholerae are the archetypes; patients can lose enough fluid and electrolytes to die without looking 'septic.'", "The one bug you cannot miss: E. coli O157:H7. EHEC O157:H7 makes a Shiga-like cytotoxin → hemolytic uremic syndrome (azotemia, microangiopathic hemolytic anemia, thrombocytopenia). Do NOT give antibiotics — they increase HUS risk. Blavo flags HUS as a recurring board question.", "Know the toxin vocabulary. Exotoxins are secreted proteins: enterotoxin (gut — cholera, Staph), neurotoxin (C. botulinum), cytotoxin (C. difficile). Endotoxin is the LPS of gram-negative bacteria, released on cell death. C. diff is a cytotoxin, not a neurotoxin.", "Work up to validate, not to fish. Most diarrhea needs no testing. Work up only red flags (moderate/severe dehydration, bloody or voluminous stool, >48 h, high fever, recent antibiotics, immunocompromised). Calprotectin/lactoferrin beat fecal leukocytes; O&P ×3 for Giardia; osmotic gap >160 = osmotic diarrhea.", "ORS is glucose-sodium cotransport — and it is first-line. Oral rehydration solution works because glucose drags sodium and water across the gut (SGLT1). WHO ORS ≈ 245 mOsm/L, Na 75, glucose 75. Sodas and juices have glucose far exceeding sodium and can worsen losses. Use ORT whenever possible.", "Reserve IV — and avoid the drug traps. IV only when ORT is not feasible (persistent vomiting, severe dehydration, ileus, aspiration risk): NS, LR, or D5NS, individualized. Bismuth → Reye syndrome in <17. Antimotility and antiemetics with caution. BRAT diet is obsolete; zinc shortens duration."], "los": [{"id": 1, "statement": "Recognize the etiology of common infectious diarrheas", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Dr. Blavo opens by deliberately downscoping the microbiology — \"we've given enough talks on those organisms\" — so the move he wants from you is not a memorized list but a pattern. Every organism collapses into one of three stool behaviors: inflammatory (EHEC, Shigella, Salmonella, Campylobacter), secretory (ETEC, Vibrio cholerae), and osmotic (rotavirus, norovirus, EPEC, Giardia). Once you know the pattern, the workup and the fluids follow — so learn the buckets, not the encyclopedia."}, {"t": "p", "x": "TOXIN VOCABULARY. Exotoxins are secreted proteins and come in three flavors the exam keeps straight: enterotoxins act on the gut surface to drive secretion (Vibrio cholerae, Staph aureus); neurotoxins damage nerves (Clostridium botulinum); and cytotoxins damage cells in any tissue (Clostridioides difficile). Endotoxin is different — it is the lipopolysaccharide of gram-negative bacteria (E. coli, Salmonella), released when the organism dies, which is why those infections keep triggering inflammation even as bacteria are killed. Blavo briefly misspoke and corrected himself here, so pin it down: C. difficile is a cytotoxin; C. botulinum is the neurotoxin."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "C. difficile makes a cytotoxin; C. botulinum makes a neurotoxin."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Endotoxin is the LPS of gram-negative bacteria, released on bacterial death."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE ONE YOU CANNOT MISS. Enterohemorrhagic E. coli (EHEC), serotype O157:H7, produces a Shiga-like cytotoxin and is the inflammatory, bloody diarrhea that progresses to hemolytic uremic syndrome — the triad of azotemia, microangiopathic hemolytic anemia, and thrombocytopenia. Blavo calls HUS out specifically as a recurring board question, and the high-yield twist lives in management: antibiotics increase the risk of HUS, so you withhold them (we return to this in LO 31.5)."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "EHEC O157:H7 → Shiga-like cytotoxin → HUS (azotemia, MAHA, thrombocytopenia)."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "Cytotoxin vs neurotoxin: C. difficile = cytotoxin (colonic mucosa); C. botulinum = neurotoxin (nerves). Blavo misspoke and corrected this in lecture."}, {"t": "trap", "x": "Reflexively giving antibiotics for \"bacterial\" bloody diarrhea — in O157:H7 they raise HUS risk. Withhold them."}, {"t": "key", "x": "Don't memorize the organism list — bucket every bug as inflammatory, secretory, or osmotic. The bucket drives workup and fluids."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Blavo says you can mostly skip memorizing the organism roll-call — so what is the one organism he tells you never to forget, and why?"}]}, {"id": 2, "statement": "Identify the clinical presentations of common infectious diarrheas", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. For diarrhea, the history is the diagnostic test — Blavo's whole \"rote-to-rationale\" message is that you ask each question for a reason. The single most useful question is the character of the stool: loose, watery, mucoid, bloody, oily, or foul-smelling. Each adjective points somewhere."}, {"t": "p", "x": "STOOL TELLS. Bloody, mucoid stool with fecal leukocytes and fever is the inflammatory pattern (mucosal invasion). Voluminous watery non-bloody stool is secretory (ETEC, cholera). Greasy, malodorous stool is the malabsorptive/osmotic picture of Giardia — its trophozoites carpet the mucosa so fat isn't absorbed. And the timing tells too: rotavirus classically causes two to three days of vomiting before the watery diarrhea begins, a sequence Blavo flags as a distinguishing clue."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Greasy, foul-smelling, non-bloody stool points to Giardia (fat malabsorption)."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Rotavirus: 2-3 days of vomiting before watery diarrhea."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE EXAM IS REALLY A DEHYDRATION EXAM. Blavo closed the first hour on this for a reason: in diarrhea, most of the physical exam is hunting for dehydration. Look for dry mucosa, decreased skin turgor, poor capillary refill, tachycardia, hypotension, sunken eyes, and reduced urine output. In an infant, the pathognomonic pair is the fontanelle: a sunken anterior fontanelle means dehydration; a bulging one means raised intracranial pressure (think meningitis). The exam loves to make you flip those two."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Infant sunken fontanelle = dehydration; bulging = raised ICP."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "The infant fontanelle is a two-way sign: sunken → dehydration, bulging → raised ICP. Same anatomy, opposite emergencies."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "Secretory = voluminous watery that persists with fasting; osmotic = smaller volume that stops with fasting. Volume + fasting separate them."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "In any diarrhea workup, assess dehydration first — it is the finding that changes your disposition fastest."}, {"t": "q", "x": "What three stool characteristics let you sort a diarrhea into inflammatory, secretory, or osmotic right at the bedside?"}]}, {"id": 3, "statement": "Recognize the differential diagnosis of common infectious diarrhea", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. There is no rigid formal classification, but the working schema gastroenterologists carry — and the one that organizes your whole differential — is inflammatory vs non-inflammatory, with non-inflammatory splitting into secretory and osmotic. The classification is the differential diagnosis."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE SECRETORY / OSMOTIC FORK. The cleanest discriminator is what happens when the patient stops eating. Secretory diarrhea is enterotoxin-driven active secretion — the lumen stays wet whether or not food is present, so it is voluminous and persists with fasting (ETEC, cholera). Osmotic diarrhea depends on an unabsorbed solute pulling water in, so it is smaller-volume and resolves with fasting (rotavirus, EPEC, Giardia). Inflammatory diarrhea sits apart, marked by blood, mucus, and fecal leukocytes."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Secretory diarrhea persists with fasting; osmotic diarrhea resolves with it."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Inflammatory = blood + fecal leukocytes + fever; non-inflammatory lacks all three."}, {"t": "p", "x": "Decision table (Type / Stool / Examples / Key tell): Inflammatory — Bloody, mucoid, fecal leukocytes, fever · EHEC, Shigella, Salmonella, Campylobacter · Blood + leukocytes ; Secretory — Voluminous watery, non-bloody · ETEC, V. cholerae · Persists with fasting ; Osmotic — Small-volume watery, ± greasy · Rotavirus, Giardia, EPEC · Resolves with fasting"}, {"t": "p", "x": "MECHANISM UNDER THE FORK. Normal absorption runs on coupled transporters — SGLT1 (Na/glucose), NHE3 (Na/H), the DRA Cl⁻/HCO₃⁻ exchanger — and on tight junctions that gate the paracellular path. Toxins tip this balance: secretion up, absorption down. You don't need the molecular detail memorized, but knowing the machinery is why ORS (next LO) even works."}, {"t": "p", "x": "INTEGRATE THE EXPOSURE HISTORY. This is Blavo's \"Cyril Why Blavo\" lesson — the differential is only as good as the targeted questions you ask to collapse it. Travel and stream/well water raise ETEC and Giardia; day-care raises rotavirus and Shigella; recent antibiotics raise C. difficile; undercooked ground beef / fast food raises O157:H7. Generate the broad list, then let one or two intentional questions sort it."}, {"t": "key", "x": "The classification IS the differential: inflammatory vs secretory vs osmotic. Place the case in a bucket and the workup and treatment fall out."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "Secretory and osmotic are both non-bloody — separate them by stool volume and the response to fasting, not by blood."}, {"t": "trap", "x": "Calling every loose-stool patient \"gastroenteritis\" — it can be IBD/IBS, not infection. The term implies infectious but doesn't prove it."}, {"t": "q", "x": "A patient has voluminous watery non-bloody diarrhea that doesn't stop when they stop eating. Secretory or osmotic — and what is the reasoning?"}]}, {"id": 4, "statement": "Identify the workup of infectious diarrheas", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Most diarrhea is mild, self-limited, and needs no workup at all — observation, fluids, and anticipatory guidance. You investigate only when a red flag raises the stakes: moderate/severe dehydration, an ill child or elderly patient, bloody or voluminous stool, duration >48 h, high fever, severe abdominal pain, recent antibiotics, or an immunocompromised host."}, {"t": "p", "x": "PICK THE TEST THAT CONFIRMS A HYPOTHESIS. Stool guaiac finds occult blood; calprotectin / lactoferrin are leukocyte proteins that detect inflammation more reliably than the fecal-leukocyte smear; stool culture & sensitivity targets bacterial causes in severe or high-risk cases; ova & parasites repeated ×3 catches Giardia a single sample misses; a stool osmotic gap >160 mOsm/kg marks osmotic diarrhea; and a urine specific gravity >1.020 with elevated BUN confirms dehydration. Blavo's frame: you order the test that validates a specific suspicion, never a shotgun panel."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Calprotectin / lactoferrin beat fecal leukocytes for detecting gut inflammation."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "A stool osmotic gap >160 mOsm/kg indicates osmotic diarrhea."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Suspected Giardia: repeat stool O&P ×3 before calling it negative."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "Work up only the red flags (bloody/voluminous, severe dehydration, >48 h, fever, recent antibiotics, immunocompromised). Otherwise observe and rehydrate."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "Calprotectin and lactoferrin are more reliable than the fecal-leukocyte smear for confirming intestinal inflammation."}, {"t": "trap", "x": "Treating one negative O&P as ruling out Giardia — sensitivity is low, so repeat ×3 when the clinical picture fits."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Blavo says a test is run \"to validate what you think, not to find the answer.\" How should that change which stool study you order?"}]}, {"id": 5, "statement": "Recognize the management of common infectious diarrheas, including fluid and electrolyte management (ORS, IV)", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Management is mostly rehydration, because most infectious diarrhea is self-limited — the body heals itself if you keep it in a workable fluid and electrolyte state. Blavo's childhood memory of a cholera outbreak in Ghana, and his later cholera intervention in Haiti, anchor the stakes: secretory losses can kill through dehydration even when the patient doesn't look classically \"septic.\" Oral rehydration is first-line."}, {"t": "p", "x": "WHY ORS WORKS. Oral rehydration solution exploits glucose-coupled sodium cotransport (SGLT1): glucose pulls sodium across the mucosa, and water follows osmotically. That coupling is why ORS must contain both glucose and sodium in balance — the WHO formulation is ~245 mOsm/L, with Na 75 and glucose 75. It also explains why sodas and fruit juices are poor substitutes: their glucose far exceeds their sodium, so the unbalanced osmotic load can actually pull more water into the gut and worsen the diarrhea — Blavo's chart showing Coca-Cola's huge sugar load makes the point."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "ORS works by glucose-sodium cotransport (SGLT1) pulling water across the gut."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Sodas/juices: glucose ≫ sodium → can worsen diarrheal losses."}, {"t": "p", "x": "WHEN TO REACH FOR IV. Use ORT whenever possible; go intravenous only when ORT is not feasible or appropriate — persistent vomiting, severe dehydration, ileus, aspiration risk, or impaired mental status. Note that mild vomiting is NOT a contraindication to ORS. IV options (normal saline, half-normal saline, lactated Ringer's, D5/NS) are individualized to severity and labs; monitor closely and transition back to ORS once the patient is resuscitated."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE DRUG TRAPS. Antibiotics are reserved for severe febrile bacterial diarrhea or the immunocompromised — empiric use is not beneficial and can be harmful: they raise HUS risk in O157:H7 and prolong fecal shedding in Salmonella. Use antimotility (loperamide) and antiemetic agents cautiously. Bismuth subsalicylate risks Reye syndrome in patients <17 (it's a salicylate). The BRAT diet is obsolete (too restrictive), while zinc shortens duration and severity."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Bismuth subsalicylate risks Reye syndrome in children <17."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "In O157:H7, antibiotics increase HUS risk — withhold them."}, {"t": "key", "x": "ORS = glucose-sodium cotransport. Both ingredients are required; the glucose is what drives the sodium-and-water absorption that rehydrates."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "ORT first, IV only when oral fails (persistent vomiting, severe dehydration, ileus, aspiration risk). Mild vomiting alone is not a contraindication."}, {"t": "trap", "x": "Empiric antibiotics / antimotility for every diarrhea — harmful in O157:H7 (HUS) and Salmonella (shedding). Treat with fluids, not reflexes."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Why is an ORS containing BOTH glucose and sodium more effective than plain water — and why is Coca-Cola a poor substitute?"}]}, {"id": 80, "statement": "Claude Concludes — Traps & Stem-Tells", "blocks": [{"t": "trap", "x": "1. Antibiotics for every bacterial diarrhea. The reflex to treat a \"bacterial\" bloody stool backfires in E. coli O157:H7, where antibiotics increase Shiga-toxin release and HUS risk. Treat with fluids. → LO 31.5"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "2. Secretory = osmotic. Both are non-bloody, but secretory is voluminous and persists with fasting; osmotic is smaller-volume and resolves with fasting. → LO 31.3"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "3. \"Vomiting, so no oral fluids.\" Mild vomiting is not a contraindication to ORS; you can still rehydrate orally while the patient vomits a little. → LO 31.5"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "4. Bismuth in a child. Bismuth subsalicylate is a salicylate → Reye syndrome risk in patients under 17. → LO 31.5"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "5. Cytotoxin vs neurotoxin. C. difficile makes a cytotoxin; the neurotoxin producer is C. botulinum. → LO 31.1"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "6. One negative O&P rules out Giardia. A single ova-and-parasite exam is insensitive — repeat it ×3 when the picture fits. → LO 31.4"}, {"t": "cue", "x": "1. \"bloody diarrhea, stool grows O157:H7\" → withhold antibiotics. Fluids only; antibiotics worsen HUS."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "2. \"voluminous watery stools, no blood, rapid dehydration\" → secretory (ETEC/cholera), not osmotic."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "3. \"child is vomiting, so mom withheld fluids\" → still give ORS; mild vomiting isn't a contraindication."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "4. \"parent gave Pepto-Bismol to a 6-year-old\" → Reye-syndrome risk (salicylate)."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "5. \"pseudomembranous colitis after antibiotics\" → C. difficile cytotoxin (not a neurotoxin)."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "6. \"one O&P negative but greasy stools persist\" → repeat O&P ×3 for Giardia."}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — Oral rehydration & antimotility/antidiarrheal pharmacology — also Lec 41 (Laxative & Antidiarrheal Agents)"}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — Secretory-vs-inflammatory reasoning reappears in the GI-bleed logic — also Lec 33-34 (GI Endoscopy), this doc"}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — Infectious vs inflammatory (IBD/IBS) overlap on the differential — revisited in later GI pathology"}]}]}, "33": {"prof": "Jeffrey Schneider, M.D.", "tldr": "Endoscopy is organized by what each scope can see and whether it is diagnostic, therapeutic, or both — and CRC screening (start at 45, colonoscopy offered first) is the single highest-yield piece.", "mustKnows": ["Diagnostic vs therapeutic vs both — tag every scope. EGD and EUS are both; ERCP is therapeutic (you already know the diagnosis); wireless capsule is diagnostic only (it can't biopsy or treat). This single frame answers most procedure questions.", "The #1 cause of a big lower-GI bleed is an upper source. A brisk upper bleed (e.g., duodenal ulcer) pumps maroon stool from below. It matters because endoscopic therapy stops upper bleeds (clip the vessel, band varices) but has limited power for lower bleeds — so exclude an upper source first.", "EUS = staging (and deep biopsy). Endoscopic ultrasound stages esophageal, gastric, and pancreatic cancer (absent widespread mets) and biopsies a pancreatic mass through the stomach wall. It is the answer to \"how do you biopsy the pancreatic mass\" — not percutaneous CT. MRCP is the noninvasive test for common-bile-duct stones.", "ERCP is the most dangerous scope — and it's therapeutic. Since MRCP, ERCP is reserved almost exclusively for therapy (relieve biliary obstruction: stones causing jaundice, gallstone pancreatitis, cholangitis; unblock a malignant duct). Complication rate ~10%; the dreaded one is post-ERCP pancreatitis.", "Barrett's → adenocarcinoma (lower esophagus). Barrett's (salmon mucosa, intestinal metaplasia) is a precursor of adenocarcinoma of the lower esophagus; the upper esophagus gives squamous cell cancer. Surveil q3-5y; don't sit on a PPI for years without a look.", "Dysphagia logic: solids vs solids-and-liquids. Solids only = a structural narrowing (cancer, EoE rings, Schatzki ring). Solids AND liquids = a motility disorder (achalasia) — get a barium study first; endoscopy looks near-normal in motility disorders.", "CRC screening: start 45; colonoscopy first. Average-risk screening starts at 45; colonoscopy q10y is offered FIRST, with annual FIT only if colonoscopy is declined. High-risk (first-degree relative <60, or two first-degree relatives): colonoscopy q5y, starting age 40 or 10 yr before the youngest affected relative.", "Cologuard = detection, not prevention. Cologuard (FIT-DNA) is 92% sensitive for cancer but only 42% for advanced adenomas — so it finds cancer, it doesn't prevent it. Every positive needs a colonoscopy; it is contraindicated in high-risk patients and is not equivalent to colonoscopy."], "los": [{"id": 1, "statement": "Describe the role of endoscopic procedures for GI hemorrhage", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Endoscopy for a GI bleed turns on two questions: is the patient hemodynamically stable or unstable, and where is the source. Unstable patients (hypotensive, tachycardic, syncope) get volume and, if exsanguinating, unmatched blood — you resuscitate before you scope."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE PPI TRICK. Before endoscopy you start an IV proton pump inhibitor. It works not by reducing pain but by clot stability: acutely raising the gastric pH toward neutral lets the platelet clot hold (clot stability = pH + platelets). In places without a gastroenterologist, that is sometimes the only bridge for hours."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "An IV PPI raises gastric pH so the clot holds (clot stability = pH + platelets)."}, {"t": "p", "x": "UPPER IS TREATABLE; LOWER OFTEN IS NOT. The role of endoscopy in a bleed is both diagnostic and therapeutic — but the therapy is far more powerful for upper pathology. A bleeding ulcer with a visible vessel of the gastroduodenal artery gets clipped; esophageal varices (portal hypertension from cirrhosis) get banded. For lower-GI bleeding the endoscopic therapeutic potential is genuinely limited."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE EXAM'S FAVORITE LINE. Schneider repeats it: the most important cause of a big lower-GI bleed is an upper GI bleed moving fast. A brisk duodenal ulcer pumps maroon stool from below — and because you can stop an upper source but mostly cannot stop a lower one, you exclude the top first in a big, unstable bleed."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Endoscopic hemostasis works far better for UPPER than LOWER GI bleeds."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "A brisk upper source is the most important cause of a big lower-GI bleed."}, {"t": "key", "x": "Endoscopy can stop upper bleeds (clip ulcers, band varices) but has limited power for lower bleeds — which is why an upper source is excluded first."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "Bleeding workup order: resuscitate (volume ± blood) → IV PPI → endoscopy to diagnose and treat."}, {"t": "trap", "x": "Assuming maroon stool = a lower source. A fast duodenal-ulcer bleed presents from below; miss it and you miss the treatable lesion."}, {"t": "q", "x": "A patient pumps out large-volume maroon stool from below. Why is your first worry an UPPER source — and what does that change about management?"}]}, {"id": 2, "statement": "Describe the use of ERCP, endoscopic ultrasound (EUS), and wireless capsule endoscopy", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Beyond the standard EGD and colonoscopy, three scopes are each defined by what they can do. The trick is to tag each one diagnostic, therapeutic, or both."}, {"t": "p", "x": "Decision table (Scope / Reaches / sees / Role / Core use): EGD — Mouth → 2nd duodenum · Both · GERD/Barrett's, ulcers, varices ; EUS — Behind stomach: pancreas, CBD, nodes · Both · Staging; biopsy pancreatic mass ; ERCP — Ampulla; bile & pancreatic ducts · Therapeutic · Relieve biliary obstruction ; Capsule — Small bowel · Dx only · Occult small-bowel bleed"}, {"t": "p", "x": "EUS = STAGING (and deep biopsy). Endoscopic ultrasound puts an ultrasound probe on the scope tip, so it sees behind the stomach — the pancreas, common bile duct, vessels, and nodes. Its indication is staging esophageal, gastric, and pancreatic cancer (in the absence of widespread metastases), and it biopsies a pancreatic mass through the stomach wall. Schneider's standing case: jaundice plus a pancreatic mass → the answer is EUS, not a percutaneous CT-guided biopsy (which risks tract seeding and undersampling). EUS also analyzes IPMN cyst fluid and diagnoses GISTs (submucosal — a surface biopsy reads normal)."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "EUS stages esophageal/gastric/pancreatic cancer and biopsies a pancreatic mass through the stomach wall."}, {"t": "p", "x": "ERCP = THERAPEUTIC. ERCP is the most dangerous procedure gastroenterologists do: a side-viewing scope reaches the ampulla, cuts a sphincterotomy, and pulls out stones. Since MRCP can diagnose noninvasively, ERCP is now reserved almost exclusively for therapy — relieving biliary obstruction (stones causing jaundice, gallstone pancreatitis, or cholangitis; unblocking a malignant duct). It does not diagnose a pancreatic mass."}, {"t": "p", "x": "WCE = DIAGNOSTIC ONLY. Wireless capsule endoscopy is a swallowed camera (the makers named it M2A) for the small bowel beyond scope reach. Its #1 indication is occult GI bleeding with a negative upper and lower endoscopy — it usually finds angiodysplasia / AVMs. It cannot biopsy or treat, you don't know exactly where it is, and it is contraindicated in stricturing Crohn disease (it can lodge and require surgery)."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "ERCP is therapeutic (relieve obstruction), not diagnostic — MRCP/EUS diagnose."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Capsule endoscopy is diagnostic-only; #1 use is occult small-bowel bleed; avoid in stricturing Crohn."}, {"t": "key", "x": "EUS = staging. It stages and biopsies a pancreatic mass through the stomach wall in one step — the answer to \"how do you biopsy it?\""}, {"t": "trap", "x": "Sending a pancreatic mass to a radiologist for percutaneous biopsy, or doing ERCP to diagnose it — both wrong. EUS stages and biopsies; ERCP only treats."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "Capsule = diagnostic only; ERCP = therapeutic; EGD and EUS = both. Tagging each scope answers most procedure questions."}, {"t": "q", "x": "A jaundiced patient has a pancreatic-head mass and no metastases. Which procedure stages AND biopsies it — and why not just send them to a radiologist?"}]}, {"id": 3, "statement": "List the disease entities and endoscopic findings of the upper gastrointestinal tract", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Upper endoscopy (EGD) sees from the oropharynx to the second portion of the duodenum. The biggest indication is GERD — and the reason to scope reflux is to look for Barrett's esophagus, a silent change in the lining."}, {"t": "p", "x": "GERD → BARRETT'S → ADENOCARCINOMA. GERD's mechanism is a loose valve — transient lower esophageal sphincter relaxation, not excess acid. Chronic reflux can produce Barrett's: salmon-colored mucosa whose biopsy shows intestinal metaplasia, a precursor of adenocarcinoma of the lower esophagus. Keep the esophagus's split straight: upper = squamous cell cancer, lower = adenocarcinoma. This is why it's irresponsible to sit on a PPI for years without a look; Barrett's gets surveyed every 3-5 years."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Barrett's (intestinal metaplasia) → adenocarcinoma of the lower esophagus; upper = squamous."}, {"t": "p", "x": "DYSPHAGIA: ONE HISTORY QUESTION. The discriminator is what gets stuck. Solids only = a structural narrowing — cancer (not in a 30-year-old), eosinophilic esophagitis (concentric rings, atopic patient, frequent food impaction), or a Schatzki ring (a single distal ring, the 'steakhouse' bolus). Solids AND liquids = a motility disorder (achalasia) — and here endoscopy is near-normal, so get a barium study first. Achalasia's birds-beak is a radiographic, not endoscopic, finding."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Solids only = structural narrowing; solids + liquids = motility (barium first)."}, {"t": "p", "x": "DYSPEPSIA, AND THE BEST-TEST TRAP. Dyspepsia (bloating, belching, no heartburn) is usually a functional motility issue; scope it when conservative measures fail or alarm features appear. While in there, you can biopsy for H. pylori and celiac disease — but Schneider's repeated burn: endoscopy is NOT the best test for either. Because both are patchy, the noninvasive tests win: urea breath / stool antigen for H. pylori and tissue transglutaminase IgA for celiac, especially to confirm eradication or diagnosis."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "For H. pylori and celiac, noninvasive tests beat endoscopic biopsy (patchy disease)."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "Barrett's = adenocarcinoma precursor (lower esophagus, intestinal metaplasia). The esophagus splits: upper squamous, lower adeno."}, {"t": "confusion", "x": "EoE = multiple concentric rings in an atopic patient with impactions; Schatzki = a single distal ring. Both cause solid dysphagia."}, {"t": "trap", "x": "Calling endoscopic biopsy the best test for H. pylori or celiac — the disease is patchy, so noninvasive tests are better."}, {"t": "q", "x": "A patient has progressive dysphagia. What single feature of the history tells you to think 'structural' versus 'motility' before any test?"}]}, {"id": 4, "statement": "Describe the use of lower endoscopic procedures for the differential diagnosis of the colorectal area", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Colonoscopy diagnoses the colorectal differential and removes polyps, but for bleeding its therapeutic reach is limited. The high-yield separations are the diverticular pair and the IBD patterns."}, {"t": "p", "x": "DIVERTICULOSIS vs DIVERTICULITIS — never mix osis and itis. DiverticulOSIS is the #1 cause of acute, painless, hemodynamically significant hematochezia over age 50, and it stops on its own ~80% of the time. DiverticulITIS is the inflamed one — left-lower-quadrant pain and fever, usually without significant bleeding — and colonoscopy is contraindicated in the acute phase. (And the seeds-and-nuts taboo is debunked.)"}, {"t": "cq", "x": "DiverticulOSIS = painless significant lower bleed (stops ~80%); diverticulITIS = LLQ pain + fever, no bleed."}, {"t": "p", "x": "OTHER LOWER BLEEDS. Angiodysplasia / AVMs weep slowly (often found on capsule); internal hemorrhoids give small-volume bright-red blood; ischemic colitis is painful bloody diarrhea at watershed zones; and colorectal cancer bleeds occultly through the adenoma-to-carcinoma sequence — the reason we screen (LO 33.6)."}, {"t": "p", "x": "IBD IS A VISUAL DIAGNOSIS. Schneider's line: \"the diagnosis is more visual than histologic.\" Crohn disease is discontinuous — skip lesions, cobblestoning, aphthous and serpiginous ulcers, anywhere mouth-to-anus. Ulcerative colitis is continuous from the rectum proximally. If you see the word cobblestoning, say Crohn's."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Crohn's = discontinuous skip lesions + cobblestoning; UC = continuous from the rectum."}, {"t": "trap", "x": "Mixing diverticulOSIS (painless bleed) and diverticulITIS (LLQ pain, fever, no bleed). Say the wrong one and you get the question wrong."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "Cobblestoning or skip lesions → Crohn's; continuous from the rectum → ulcerative colitis. IBD is read more by eye than by biopsy."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "Acute painless significant hematochezia in the elderly → diverticulosis (stops ~80%); first exclude a fast upper source."}, {"t": "q", "x": "An elderly patient has acute, painless, large-volume hematochezia and is stable. What is the most likely source, and why is endoscopic therapy limited?"}]}, {"id": 5, "statement": "Understand the indications and complications of endoscopy", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Indications run through the other LOs; the complications and contraindications are the testable headlines. ERCP is the most dangerous procedure gastroenterologists perform, with an overall complication rate around 10%. Its signature complication is post-ERCP pancreatitis — you are working at the tiny opening where the bile and pancreatic ducts meet, so even a flawless operator can inflame the pancreas."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "ERCP is the most dangerous GI scope (~10% complications); the dreaded one is post-ERCP pancreatitis."}, {"t": "p", "x": "CONTRAINDICATIONS WORTH KNOWING. Colonoscopy is contraindicated in acute diverticulitis (abdominal inflammation — you don't push a scope through it). Wireless capsule is contraindicated in stricturing Crohn disease (it can lodge). General complications across scopes include bleeding and perforation; ERCP adds bleeding from the sphincterotomy and duodenal perforation."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Colonoscopy is contraindicated in acute diverticulitis; capsule in stricturing Crohn's."}, {"t": "trap", "x": "Forgetting that ERCP — not the bigger-looking colonoscopy — is the highest-risk scope, because of post-ERCP pancreatitis."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "Don't scope through inflammation: acute diverticulitis contraindicates colonoscopy; stricturing Crohn's contraindicates the capsule."}, {"t": "key", "x": "The two procedure headlines: ERCP = most dangerous (pancreatitis ~10%); capsule = safest but powerless (diagnostic only, can lodge in a stricture)."}, {"t": "q", "x": "Which endoscopic procedure carries the highest complication rate, and what is its signature complication?"}]}, {"id": 6, "statement": "State the colonoscopy and the screening recommendations of the American College of Gastroenterology", "blocks": [{"t": "p", "x": "OVERVIEW. Schneider calls screening his primary responsibility — and the single highest-yield block. The logic is the adenoma-to-carcinoma sequence: precancerous adenomatous polyps become cancer over roughly a decade, so we scope to find and remove them."}, {"t": "p", "x": "THE NUMBERS (2022 update). Average-risk screening now starts at 45 (down from 50; African Americans also 45). Colonoscopy every 10 years is offered FIRST; annual FIT is for patients who decline colonoscopy — not an equal menu option. Individualize ages 76-85; stop routine screening by 85 (or earlier when life expectancy is under ~10 years)."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Average-risk CRC screening: start 45; colonoscopy q10y offered first; annual FIT if declined."}, {"t": "p", "x": "HIGH-RISK TIMING. A first-degree relative with CRC/advanced adenoma under 60, or two first-degree relatives at any age, makes a patient high-risk: colonoscopy every 5 years, starting at age 40 OR 10 years before the youngest affected relative, whichever is earlier. (Relative diagnosed at 55 → start at 45 by the math, but 40 is earlier, so start 40.)"}, {"t": "cq", "x": "High-risk: colonoscopy q5y, start 40 or 10 yr before the youngest affected relative."}, {"t": "p", "x": "COLOGUARD — DETECTION, NOT PREVENTION. Cologuard is FIT-DNA (FIT plus a methylated-DNA assay), repeated every 3 years. It is ~92% sensitive for cancer but only ~42% for advanced adenomas — so it finds cancer but doesn't prevent it (you can't remove a polyp through a stool test). Every positive needs a colonoscopy; only ~4% of positives have cancer; and it is contraindicated in high-risk patients. Offer it only to someone refusing colonoscopy — never as an equivalent."}, {"t": "cq", "x": "Cologuard (FIT-DNA, q3y) = 92% cancer / 42% advanced adenoma → detection, not prevention."}, {"t": "p", "x": "Decision table (Group / Start / Interval / Notes): Average-risk — 45 · Colonoscopy q10y (first) · Annual FIT only if colonoscopy declined ; High-risk — 40, or 10 yr before youngest case · Colonoscopy q5y · FDR <60, or two FDRs ; Cologuard (FIT-DNA) — — · q3y · 92% cancer / 42% adenoma; not high-risk"}, {"t": "key", "x": "Average-risk: start 45, colonoscopy q10y offered first, annual FIT only if declined. High-risk: q5y, start 40 or 10 yr before the youngest case."}, {"t": "trap", "x": "Telling a patient a stool test equals colonoscopy — colonoscopy is offered first; FIT/Cologuard are for those who decline, and Cologuard is not equivalent."}, {"t": "pearl", "x": "Cologuard = detection, not prevention: great at finding cancer (92%), poor at advanced adenomas (42%), useless in high-risk, and every positive still needs a colonoscopy."}, {"t": "q", "x": "A patient's primary-care office told them a stool test is an equal alternative to colonoscopy. What is wrong with that, and what should have been said?"}]}, {"id": 80, "statement": "Claude Concludes — Traps & Stem-Tells", "blocks": [{"t": "trap", "x": "1. ERCP for diagnosis. ERCP is therapeutic (relieve obstruction); diagnose with EUS / MRCP. With MRCP available, ERCP is reserved for treatment. → LO 33.2"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "2. \"Endoscopy is the best test for H. pylori / celiac.\" Both are patchy, so noninvasive tests (urea breath / stool antigen; tTG-IgA) are better. → LO 33.3"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "3. DiverticulOSIS = diverticulITIS. OSIS = painless significant bleed; ITIS = LLQ pain + fever, no bleed (and colonoscopy is contraindicated). → LO 33.4"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "4. Stopping a lower-GI bleed endoscopically. Endoscopic therapy is limited below; upper bleeds you can clip or band. → LO 33.1"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "5. Barrett's → squamous. Barrett's → adenocarcinoma of the lower esophagus; squamous is the upper esophagus. → LO 33.3"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "6. Biopsy a pancreatic mass percutaneously. Use EUS — it stages and biopsies through the stomach wall; percutaneous biopsy risks seeding. → LO 33.2"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "7. \"Stool test or colonoscopy — your choice.\" Colonoscopy is offered FIRST; FIT is for those who decline, and Cologuard is not equivalent. → LO 33.6"}, {"t": "trap", "x": "8. Cologuard for everyone (and high-risk). It is detection-not-prevention, only 42% for advanced adenomas, and contraindicated in high-risk. → LO 33.6"}, {"t": "cue", "x": "1. \"we did an ERCP to find out what was going on\" → wrong framing; ERCP treats, EUS/MRCP diagnose."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "2. \"scope biopsy was negative for H. pylori, so it's gone\" → confirm with urea breath / stool antigen."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "3. \"elderly, painless, large-volume maroon stool, stable\" → diverticulosis (after excluding a fast upper source)."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "4. \"brisk maroon stool, hypotensive\" → think upper source moving fast (treatable), not just \"lower bleed.\""}, {"t": "cue", "x": "5. \"salmon tongue above the GE junction, years on a PPI\" → Barrett's → adenocarcinoma; surveil q3-5y."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "6. \"jaundice + pancreatic-head mass, how do you biopsy?\" → EUS, not percutaneous."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "7. \"told the stool test is equivalent to colonoscopy\" → colonoscopy first; FIT only if colonoscopy refused."}, {"t": "cue", "x": "8. \"Cologuard was negative, so reassured\" → only 42% for advanced adenomas; detection, not prevention."}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — H. pylori testing & acid-suppression pharmacology — also Lec 35 (Drugs for Peptic Ulcers & Gastric Acidity)"}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — Esophageal varices, portal hypertension & cirrhosis — also Lec 39-40 (Chronic Liver Disease)"}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — ERCP, choledocholithiasis & biliary obstruction — also Lec 44-45 (Pathology / Surgery of the Biliary Tract)"}, {"t": "p", "x": "Cross-lecture links — DiverticulOSIS (bleed) vs diverticulITIS (inflammation) — also Lec 38 (Abdominal Pain / Diverticulitis)"}]}]}};
const LECTURE_REFERENCES = {};

// QUIZ_START
const QUIZ = [[31, "Infectious Diarrhea (Lec 31–32)", [[1, "Recognize the etiology of common infectious diarrheas", [["A traveler returns with profuse, voluminous, watery, non-bloody diarrhea and rapid dehydration. The most likely organism is:", ["Enterotoxigenic E. coli", "Enterohemorrhagic E. coli", "Shigella sonnei", "Campylobacter jejuni", "Salmonella typhi"], 0, "Voluminous watery non-bloody stools with rapid dehydration is the secretory pattern. ETEC is the classic traveler's-diarrhea enterotoxin producer; cholera is the other archetype.\n\nWhy not — Enterohemorrhagic E. coli: EHEC is inflammatory — bloody stools and HUS, not voluminous watery.  Shigella sonnei: Shigella is inflammatory dysentery — bloody, mucoid, febrile.  Campylobacter jejuni: Campylobacter is inflammatory and often poultry-linked, not secretory.  Salmonella typhi: Salmonella typhi is inflammatory/systemic, not a watery secretory bug.", "advanced"], ["Clostridioides difficile damages colonic cells through which type of toxin?", ["Cytotoxin", "Neurotoxin", "Endotoxin", "Enterotoxin", "Superantigen"], 0, "C. difficile produces cytotoxins (toxins A/B) that damage colonic mucosa. Blavo self-corrected in lecture: the neurotoxin producer is C. botulinum, not C. difficile.\n\nWhy not — Neurotoxin: Neurotoxin is C. botulinum (botulism), which damages nerves.  Endotoxin: Endotoxin is LPS released on gram-negative cell death, not a C. diff product.  Enterotoxin: Enterotoxins (cholera, Staph) act on the gut surface to drive secretion.  Superantigen: Superantigens drive massive T-cell activation, not C. diff colitis.", "basic"], ["Bloody diarrhea from E. coli O157:H7 progresses to renal failure, hemolysis, and thrombocytopenia. The complication is:", ["Hemolytic uremic syndrome", "Disseminated intravascular coagulation", "Reye syndrome", "Thrombotic thrombocytopenic purpura", "Guillain-Barré syndrome"], 0, "The classic triad — azotemia, microangiopathic hemolytic anemia, and thrombocytopenia — is hemolytic uremic syndrome, driven by the Shiga-like toxin of EHEC O157:H7.\n\nWhy not — Disseminated intravascular coagulation: DIC has consumptive coagulopathy with bleeding and abnormal coags, not the HUS triad.  Reye syndrome: Reye syndrome is salicylate-associated hepatic/cerebral injury, not an O157:H7 sequela.  Thrombotic thrombocytopenic purpura: TTP shares MAHA but is ADAMTS13-related with neuro signs and fever, not O157:H7.  Guillain-Barré syndrome: Guillain-Barré (ascending paralysis) follows Campylobacter, not O157:H7.", "basic"], ["An endotoxin that triggers inflammation only when the bacterium dies is best described as the:", ["Lipopolysaccharide of gram-negative bacteria", "Exotoxin of gram-positive bacteria", "Secreted protein of gram-positive bacteria", "Capsular polysaccharide of gram-negative bacteria", "Teichoic acid of gram-positive bacteria"], 0, "Endotoxin is the lipopolysaccharide (LPS) of the gram-negative outer membrane, released on cell lysis to trigger inflammation — distinct from secreted exotoxins.\n\nWhy not — Exotoxin of gram-positive bacteria: Exotoxins are actively secreted, not released only on death.  Secreted protein of gram-positive bacteria: Secreted proteins are exotoxins, released by living bacteria.  Capsular polysaccharide of gram-negative bacteria: Capsular polysaccharide is an anti-phagocytic coat, not endotoxin.  Teichoic acid of gram-positive bacteria: Teichoic acid is a gram-positive wall component, not LPS.", "basic"]]], [2, "Identify the clinical presentations of common infectious diarrheas", [["Greasy, malodorous, non-bloody stools with fat malabsorption most suggest:", ["Giardia duodenalis", "Shigella sonnei", "Enterohemorrhagic E. coli", "Vibrio cholerae", "Salmonella typhi"], 0, "Giardia trophozoites line the mucosa and blunt fat absorption, producing oily, foul-smelling, non-bloody stools — the classic osmotic/malabsorptive picture.\n\nWhy not — Shigella sonnei: Shigella is bloody inflammatory dysentery, not greasy malabsorption.  Enterohemorrhagic E. coli: EHEC is bloody and inflammatory, not fatty.  Vibrio cholerae: Cholera is voluminous watery secretory, not greasy.  Salmonella typhi: Salmonella is inflammatory/systemic, not a malabsorptive picture.", "basic"], ["Frequent moderate-volume bloody mucoid stools with fecal leukocytes and fever indicate which diarrhea type?", ["Inflammatory diarrhea", "Secretory diarrhea", "Osmotic diarrhea", "Factitious diarrhea", "Functional diarrhea"], 0, "Blood, mucus, fecal leukocytes, and fever signal mucosal invasion/damage — the inflammatory pattern (EHEC, Shigella, Salmonella, Campylobacter).\n\nWhy not — Secretory diarrhea: Secretory diarrhea is voluminous watery and non-bloody, without leukocytes.  Osmotic diarrhea: Osmotic diarrhea is non-bloody and resolves with fasting.  Factitious diarrhea: Factitious (laxative) diarrhea lacks blood and fecal leukocytes.  Functional diarrhea: Functional diarrhea has no inflammatory markers or fever.", "basic"], ["Which finding most specifically signals dehydration in an infant?", ["Sunken anterior fontanelle", "Bulging anterior fontanelle", "Brisk capillary refill", "Increased skin turgor", "Excessive tearing"], 0, "A sunken anterior fontanelle reflects reduced body fluid (dehydration); a bulging fontanelle reflects raised intracranial pressure (e.g., meningitis) — the opposite concern.\n\nWhy not — Bulging anterior fontanelle: A bulging fontanelle suggests raised ICP, not dehydration.  Brisk capillary refill: Brisk capillary refill is normal perfusion, not dehydration.  Increased skin turgor: Dehydration decreases skin turgor; it does not increase it.  Excessive tearing: Reduced (not excessive) tearing accompanies dehydration.", "basic"], ["A child vomits for two to three days before watery diarrhea begins. The most likely agent is:", ["Rotavirus", "Vibrio cholerae", "Giardia duodenalis", "Enterotoxigenic E. coli", "Entamoeba histolytica"], 0, "Rotavirus characteristically causes several days of vomiting before watery diarrhea — Blavo's point that the vomiting-to-diarrhea sequence distinguishes one case from another.\n\nWhy not — Vibrio cholerae: Cholera presents with abrupt voluminous watery diarrhea, not a vomiting prodrome.  Giardia duodenalis: Giardia is subacute greasy diarrhea, not a vomiting prodrome.  Enterotoxigenic E. coli: ETEC is acute traveler's watery diarrhea without the prodrome.  Entamoeba histolytica: E. histolytica causes dysentery/abscesses, not a vomiting prodrome.", "advanced"]]], [3, "Recognize the differential diagnosis of common infectious diarrhea", [["Compared with osmotic diarrhea, secretory diarrhea is characterized by:", ["Voluminous watery stools that persist with fasting", "Small-volume stools that resolve with fasting", "Bloody mucoid stools with fecal leukocytes", "Greasy stools with prominent fat malabsorption", "Stools driven by a high stool osmotic gap"], 0, "Secretory diarrhea is enterotoxin-driven active secretion: voluminous, watery, and it continues even when the patient stops eating. Osmotic diarrhea depends on ingested solute and stops with fasting.\n\nWhy not — Small-volume stools that resolve with fasting: Resolving with fasting is the osmotic pattern.  Bloody mucoid stools with fecal leukocytes: Blood and leukocytes define inflammatory, not secretory, diarrhea.  Greasy stools with prominent fat malabsorption: Greasy malabsorptive stool is the osmotic/Giardia pattern.  Stools driven by a high stool osmotic gap: A high osmotic gap defines osmotic, not secretory, diarrhea.", "basic"], ["A traveler has one week of greasy, foul-smelling, non-bloody diarrhea with bloating; one stool O&P is negative. The best read is:", ["Giardia, and repeat stool ova-and-parasite testing", "ETEC, and give oral rehydration salts", "Vibrio cholerae, and start IV crystalloid", "Norovirus, and simply reassure the patient", "EHEC, and strictly avoid all antibiotics"], 0, "Greasy, malodorous, bloating, subacute non-bloody diarrhea after travel is Giardia. A single O&P is insensitive — repeat it up to three times before excluding the parasite.\n\nWhy not — ETEC, and give oral rehydration salts: ETEC is acute voluminous watery diarrhea, not greasy and bloating.  Vibrio cholerae, and start IV crystalloid: Cholera is voluminous watery secretory, not greasy malabsorption.  Norovirus, and simply reassure the patient: Norovirus is acute self-limited vomiting/diarrhea, not weeks of greasy stool.  EHEC, and strictly avoid all antibiotics: EHEC is bloody inflammatory diarrhea, not greasy non-bloody.", "advanced"], ["A patient has profuse watery non-bloody diarrhea with severe dehydration and no fever. The priority intervention is:", ["Aggressive fluid and electrolyte replacement", "Empiric oral ciprofloxacin therapy", "Loperamide to slow gut motility", "Bismuth subsalicylate for symptoms", "Stool culture before any treatment"], 0, "This is the secretory/cholera-like pattern; the immediate threat is fluid and electrolyte loss, so rehydration comes first — diagnostics and drugs do not precede resuscitation.\n\nWhy not — Empiric oral ciprofloxacin therapy: Empiric antibiotics are not first-line and can harm (e.g., O157:H7).  Loperamide to slow gut motility: Antimotility agents are used with caution and don't treat dehydration.  Bismuth subsalicylate for symptoms: Bismuth treats symptoms, not the life-threatening fluid loss.  Stool culture before any treatment: Culture doesn't change the immediate need to rehydrate.", "advanced"]]], [4, "Identify the workup of infectious diarrheas", [["Which feature most justifies a diagnostic work-up rather than observation alone?", ["Bloody stools with high fever", "Two days of mild watery stools", "A single loose stool after travel", "Self-limited nausea without diarrhea", "Normal vital signs and good hydration"], 0, "Bloody stools plus high fever flags an inflammatory/invasive process and the need for testing. Mild, brief, well-hydrated cases are observed, not worked up.\n\nWhy not — Two days of mild watery stools: Mild brief watery stools are observed, not investigated.  A single loose stool after travel: A single loose stool needs no work-up.  Self-limited nausea without diarrhea: Nausea without diarrhea is not an indication to test stool.  Normal vital signs and good hydration: Normal vitals and hydration argue against work-up.", "basic"], ["Which stool test most reliably confirms intestinal inflammation?", ["Fecal calprotectin", "Fecal leukocytes", "Stool guaiac", "Stool osmotic gap", "Urine specific gravity"], 0, "Stool calprotectin (and lactoferrin) are leukocyte proteins that detect intestinal inflammation more reliably than the older fecal-leukocyte smear.\n\nWhy not — Fecal leukocytes: Fecal leukocytes are less sensitive/reliable than calprotectin.  Stool guaiac: Guaiac detects occult blood, not inflammation per se.  Stool osmotic gap: The osmotic gap separates osmotic from secretory, not inflammation.  Urine specific gravity: Urine specific gravity gauges hydration, not gut inflammation.", "basic"], ["A stool osmotic gap above 160 mOsm/kg most supports which diarrhea type?", ["Osmotic diarrhea", "Secretory diarrhea", "Inflammatory diarrhea", "Bacillary dysentery", "Antibiotic-associated colitis"], 0, "A high stool osmotic gap means an unabsorbed osmotically active solute is driving water into the lumen — the definition of osmotic diarrhea. Secretory diarrhea has a low gap.\n\nWhy not — Secretory diarrhea: Secretory diarrhea has a LOW osmotic gap (electrolyte-driven).  Inflammatory diarrhea: Inflammatory diarrhea is defined by blood/leukocytes, not the gap.  Bacillary dysentery: Dysentery is inflammatory, characterized by blood, not the gap.  Antibiotic-associated colitis: C. diff colitis is inflammatory, not gap-defined.", "advanced"], ["A urine specific gravity above 1.020 with an elevated BUN most suggests:", ["Dehydration", "Overhydration", "Active GI bleeding", "Bacterial coinfection", "Lactose intolerance"], 0, "Concentrated urine (SG >1.020) and a rising BUN are markers of volume depletion — Blavo's point that the test confirms the dehydration you already suspect.\n\nWhy not — Overhydration: Overhydration produces dilute urine and a low-normal BUN.  Active GI bleeding: GI bleeding is suggested by guaiac/hematochezia, not urine SG.  Bacterial coinfection: Coinfection is suggested by leukocytosis, not urine concentration.  Lactose intolerance: Lactose intolerance relates to the osmotic gap, not urine SG.", "advanced"]]], [5, "Recognize the management of common infectious diarrheas, including fluid and electrolyte management (ORS, IV)", [["Oral rehydration solution works primarily because glucose drives absorption of:", ["Sodium and water across the gut", "Potassium and water across the gut", "Chloride against its electrochemical gradient", "Bicarbonate into the intestinal lumen", "Protein across the mucosal barrier"], 0, "ORS exploits glucose-coupled sodium cotransport (SGLT1): glucose pulls sodium in, and water follows osmotically — which is why ORS needs both glucose and sodium.\n\nWhy not — Potassium and water across the gut: Cotransport is glucose-SODIUM, not glucose-potassium.  Chloride against its electrochemical gradient: Chloride is not the cotransported species in SGLT1.  Bicarbonate into the intestinal lumen: Bicarbonate secretion is not the ORS mechanism.  Protein across the mucosal barrier: Protein is not cotransported with glucose for rehydration.", "basic"], ["Why are sodas and fruit juices poor rehydration fluids in diarrhea?", ["Glucose far exceeds sodium content", "Sodium far exceeds glucose content", "They are essentially isotonic fluids", "They contain excessive potassium content", "They contain no usable carbohydrate"], 0, "Sodas/juices have glucose vastly exceeding sodium; the unbalanced osmotic load lacks the sodium needed for cotransport and can pull more water into the lumen, worsening losses.\n\nWhy not — Sodium far exceeds glucose content: It's the reverse — glucose exceeds sodium in these drinks.  They are essentially isotonic fluids: They are hyperosmolar, not isotonic.  They contain excessive potassium content: Excess potassium is not the issue; the glucose:sodium ratio is.  They contain no usable carbohydrate: They contain plenty of carbohydrate — that's the problem.", "basic"], ["When is intravenous rehydration preferred over oral rehydration?", ["Persistent vomiting with severe dehydration", "Mild dehydration tolerating oral fluids", "Mild vomiting without bowel obstruction", "A stable child drinking fluids well", "Self-limited mild watery diarrhea"], 0, "IV is reserved for when ORT is not feasible or safe — persistent vomiting, severe dehydration, ileus, or aspiration risk. Mild vomiting alone is not a contraindication to ORS.\n\nWhy not — Mild dehydration tolerating oral fluids: Mild dehydration tolerating fluids is treated orally.  Mild vomiting without bowel obstruction: Mild vomiting without obstruction still allows ORS.  A stable child drinking fluids well: A child drinking well does not need IV.  Self-limited mild watery diarrhea: Self-limited mild diarrhea needs oral fluids at most.", "basic"], ["Bismuth subsalicylate is avoided in children under 17 because of the risk for:", ["Reye syndrome", "Hemolytic uremic syndrome", "Serotonin syndrome", "Clostridioides difficile colitis", "Lactic acidosis"], 0, "Bismuth subsalicylate contains a salicylate; in children/teens this carries Reye-syndrome risk — Blavo notes it is a frequent exam point.\n\nWhy not — Hemolytic uremic syndrome: HUS is the O157:H7 sequela, not a bismuth effect.  Serotonin syndrome: Serotonin syndrome is a serotonergic-drug effect, unrelated.  Clostridioides difficile colitis: C. diff colitis follows broad antibiotics, not bismuth.  Lactic acidosis: Lactic acidosis is not the bismuth concern in children.", "advanced"], ["A child with bloody diarrhea and confirmed E. coli O157:H7 should NOT receive antibiotics because they:", ["Increase hemolytic uremic syndrome risk", "Meaningfully shorten the diarrheal illness", "Reliably eradicate the Shiga toxin", "Completely prevent further fecal shedding", "Have no effect on the clinical course"], 0, "Antibiotics can increase Shiga-toxin release and the risk of HUS in O157:H7, so they are withheld; fluids and supportive care are the mainstay.\n\nWhy not — Meaningfully shorten the diarrheal illness: Antibiotics do not reliably shorten the illness here.  Reliably eradicate the Shiga toxin: They do not eradicate the toxin — they can increase its release.  Completely prevent further fecal shedding: They do not reliably stop shedding (and can prolong Salmonella carriage).  Have no effect on the clinical course: They are not neutral — they are potentially harmful.", "advanced"]]]]], [33, "GI Endoscopy (Lec 33–34)", [[1, "Describe the role of endoscopic procedures for GI hemorrhage", [["A patient pumps out large-volume maroon stool and is hemodynamically unstable. The most important source to exclude FIRST is:", ["A brisk upper GI source moving fast", "Internal hemorrhoids of the rectum", "Diverticulosis of the sigmoid colon", "Angiodysplasia of the cecum", "Ischemic colitis of the splenic flexure"], 0, "A fast upper bleed (e.g., duodenal ulcer) is the most important cause of a big lower-GI bleed — and, unlike most lower sources, you can stop it endoscopically. Exclude it first.\n\nWhy not — Internal hemorrhoids of the rectum: Hemorrhoids cause small-volume bright-red bleeding, not unstable maroon stool.  Diverticulosis of the sigmoid colon: Diverticulosis bleeds but is the answer for painless STABLE elderly hematochezia.  Angiodysplasia of the cecum: Angiodysplasia usually weeps slowly, rarely causing instability first.  Ischemic colitis of the splenic flexure: Ischemic colitis causes pain and bloody diarrhea, not brisk maroon exsanguination.", "advanced"], ["Endoscopic therapy to STOP active bleeding is far more effective for:", ["Upper GI bleeding lesions", "Lower GI bleeding lesions", "Cecal vascular ectasias", "Diverticular bleeding sites", "Small-bowel angiodysplasias"], 0, "The therapeutic potential of endoscopy is much greater for UPPER pathology (clip an ulcer vessel, band varices); lower-GI bleeding has limited endoscopic therapy.\n\nWhy not — Lower GI bleeding lesions: Lower-GI bleeding has limited endoscopic therapeutic options.  Cecal vascular ectasias: Cecal ectasias are lower-tract lesions with limited durable therapy.  Diverticular bleeding sites: Diverticular bleeding usually stops on its own; endoscopic control is limited.  Small-bowel angiodysplasias: Small-bowel AVMs are hard to reach and treat durably.", "basic"], ["Why is an IV proton pump inhibitor given for an acute bleeding ulcer?", ["Raising gastric pH stabilizes the clot", "It directly cauterizes the bleeding vessel", "It replaces the lost circulating volume", "It rapidly reverses anticoagulation", "It immediately eradicates Helicobacter pylori"], 0, "Clot stability depends on pH and platelets; acutely raising gastric pH toward neutral lets the clot hold while you arrange endoscopy.\n\nWhy not — It directly cauterizes the bleeding vessel: The PPI doesn't cauterize — endoscopic clips/thermal therapy do.  It replaces the lost circulating volume: Volume is replaced with fluids/blood, not a PPI.  It rapidly reverses anticoagulation: A PPI does not reverse anticoagulation.  It immediately eradicates Helicobacter pylori: H. pylori eradication takes a multi-drug course, not an acute PPI.", "basic"], ["Sudden massive bright-red hematemesis in a patient with cirrhosis is most likely from:", ["Esophageal varices", "A Mallory-Weiss tear", "Erosive gastritis", "A Schatzki ring", "Reflux esophagitis"], 0, "Portal hypertension from cirrhosis produces esophageal varices, which can bleed massively and painlessly — sometimes the presenting sign of unrecognized cirrhosis.\n\nWhy not — A Mallory-Weiss tear: A Mallory-Weiss tear is a benign, usually self-limited bleed after retching.  Erosive gastritis: Erosive gastritis oozes; it rarely causes massive variceal-type hemorrhage.  A Schatzki ring: A Schatzki ring causes dysphagia, not hemorrhage.  Reflux esophagitis: Reflux esophagitis bleeds little and isn't the cirrhosis association.", "advanced"]]], [2, "Describe the use of ERCP, endoscopic ultrasound (EUS), and wireless capsule endoscopy", [["A jaundiced patient has a pancreatic-head mass and no distant metastases. The best way to stage AND biopsy it is:", ["Endoscopic ultrasound", "ERCP with duct brushings", "Percutaneous CT-guided biopsy", "Wireless capsule endoscopy", "Upper endoscopy with biopsy"], 0, "EUS biopsies the mass through the stomach wall, assesses vascular involvement, and samples nodes — all in one staging procedure; percutaneous biopsy risks tract seeding and undersampling.\n\nWhy not — ERCP with duct brushings: ERCP relieves obstruction; it rarely gets a tissue diagnosis of the mass.  Percutaneous CT-guided biopsy: Percutaneous biopsy risks tract seeding and may undersample.  Wireless capsule endoscopy: Capsule endoscopy cannot reach or biopsy the pancreas.  Upper endoscopy with biopsy: A forward-viewing EGD can't see or sample a mass behind the stomach.", "advanced"], ["Since the advent of MRCP, ERCP is reserved almost exclusively for:", ["Therapeutic relief of biliary obstruction", "Diagnosis of pancreatic masses", "Routine evaluation of abnormal liver tests", "Staging of esophageal cancer", "Screening for common-bile-duct stones"], 0, "ERCP is the most dangerous GI procedure; with MRCP available for diagnosis, ERCP is done to TREAT — sphincterotomy and stone extraction to relieve obstruction.\n\nWhy not — Diagnosis of pancreatic masses: Pancreatic masses are diagnosed by EUS, not ERCP.  Routine evaluation of abnormal liver tests: Abnormal liver tests are worked up noninvasively first.  Staging of esophageal cancer: Esophageal cancer is staged by EUS.  Screening for common-bile-duct stones: CBD stones are screened noninvasively with MRCP.", "basic"], ["Wireless capsule endoscopy is best suited for evaluating:", ["Occult bleeding of the small intestine", "Therapy of a bleeding duodenal ulcer", "Biopsy of a submucosal gastric mass", "Removal of a pedunculated colon polyp", "Staging of an early gastric cancer"], 0, "Capsule endoscopy is diagnostic-only and shines in the small bowel beyond scope reach; its #1 indication is occult GI bleeding (negative upper and lower), typically finding AVMs.\n\nWhy not — Therapy of a bleeding duodenal ulcer: The capsule cannot treat anything — it only takes pictures.  Biopsy of a submucosal gastric mass: It cannot biopsy a mass.  Removal of a pedunculated colon polyp: It cannot perform polypectomy.  Staging of an early gastric cancer: It cannot stage tumors or reliably image the stomach.", "basic"], ["Wireless capsule endoscopy is contraindicated in a patient with known:", ["Stricturing Crohn disease", "Iron-deficiency anemia", "Occult GI bleeding", "A prior negative colonoscopy", "Small-bowel angiodysplasia"], 0, "A stricture can trap the capsule, requiring surgical retrieval; known stricturing Crohn disease is a contraindication.\n\nWhy not — Iron-deficiency anemia: Iron-deficiency anemia is an indication, not a contraindication.  Occult GI bleeding: Occult GI bleeding is the #1 indication.  A prior negative colonoscopy: A prior negative colonoscopy is part of the occult-bleed workup, not a contraindication.  Small-bowel angiodysplasia: Angiodysplasia is exactly what capsule endoscopy looks for.", "advanced"]]], [3, "List the disease entities and endoscopic findings of the upper gastrointestinal tract", [["Barrett esophagus is a precursor to which malignancy?", ["Esophageal adenocarcinoma", "Esophageal squamous cell carcinoma", "Gastric adenocarcinoma", "Pancreatic adenocarcinoma", "Duodenal carcinoid tumor"], 0, "Barrett's (intestinal metaplasia from chronic reflux) is the precursor of adenocarcinoma of the lower esophagus — not squamous cell carcinoma.\n\nWhy not — Esophageal squamous cell carcinoma: Squamous cell carcinoma arises in the UPPER esophagus, unrelated to Barrett's.  Gastric adenocarcinoma: Gastric adenocarcinoma is not the Barrett's sequela.  Pancreatic adenocarcinoma: Pancreatic cancer is unrelated to Barrett's.  Duodenal carcinoid tumor: Duodenal carcinoid is unrelated to Barrett's.", "basic"], ["Squamous cell carcinoma of the esophagus classically arises in the:", ["Upper esophagus", "Lower esophagus", "Gastroesophageal junction", "Gastric antrum", "Duodenal bulb"], 0, "The upper esophagus gives squamous cell carcinoma; the lower esophagus (Barrett-associated) gives adenocarcinoma. The esophagus is 'tricky' precisely because the two split by location.\n\nWhy not — Lower esophagus: The lower esophagus gives adenocarcinoma (Barrett-related).  Gastroesophageal junction: The GE junction is the adenocarcinoma/Barrett zone.  Gastric antrum: The gastric antrum is stomach, not esophagus.  Duodenal bulb: The duodenal bulb is small bowel, not esophagus.", "basic"], ["Progressive dysphagia to SOLIDS ONLY most suggests a:", ["Fixed structural narrowing", "Primary esophageal motility disorder", "Functional swallowing complaint", "Diffuse esophageal spasm", "Globus sensation from anxiety"], 0, "Solids-only dysphagia points to a structural narrowing (cancer, EoE, Schatzki ring); dysphagia to BOTH solids and liquids points to a motility disorder — get a barium study first there.\n\nWhy not — Primary esophageal motility disorder: Motility disorders cause solid AND liquid dysphagia.  Functional swallowing complaint: Functional complaints don't progress with a fixed pattern.  Diffuse esophageal spasm: Spasm causes intermittent solid-and-liquid dysphagia.  Globus sensation from anxiety: Globus is a constant lump sensation, not progressive solid dysphagia.", "basic"], ["Concentric esophageal rings (a 'corrugated' esophagus) with recurrent food impaction in an atopic patient indicate:", ["Eosinophilic esophagitis", "A Schatzki ring", "Esophageal adenocarcinoma", "Achalasia of the sphincter", "A peptic reflux stricture"], 0, "Eosinophilic esophagitis is an allergic esophagus producing multiple concentric rings and frequent food impaction in atopic patients; a Schatzki ring is a single distal ring.\n\nWhy not — A Schatzki ring: A Schatzki ring is a SINGLE distal ring, not multiple rings.  Esophageal adenocarcinoma: Adenocarcinoma is a mass/stricture, not concentric rings in a young atopic.  Achalasia of the sphincter: Achalasia has near-normal endoscopy, not rings.  A peptic reflux stricture: A peptic stricture is a single tight narrowing, not corrugated rings.", "advanced"]]], [4, "Describe the use of lower endoscopic procedures for the differential diagnosis of the colorectal area", [["The most common cause of acute, painless, hemodynamically significant hematochezia in an elderly patient is:", ["Diverticulosis", "Diverticulitis", "Internal hemorrhoids", "Ischemic colitis", "Colorectal carcinoma"], 0, "Diverticulosis is the classic cause of acute, painless, large-volume lower-GI bleeding over age 50; it stops on its own in roughly 80%.\n\nWhy not — Diverticulitis: DiverticulITIS causes pain and fever, typically WITHOUT significant bleeding.  Internal hemorrhoids: Hemorrhoids cause small-volume bright-red bleeding.  Ischemic colitis: Ischemic colitis is painful with bloody diarrhea, not painless.  Colorectal carcinoma: Colorectal cancer usually bleeds slowly/occultly, not acutely and massively.", "advanced"], ["A patient with left-lower-quadrant pain and fever but no bleeding most likely has:", ["Diverticulitis", "Diverticulosis", "Angiodysplasia", "Internal hemorrhoids", "A colonic adenoma"], 0, "DiverticulITIS = inflammation: LLQ pain and fever, usually WITHOUT significant bleeding (and colonoscopy is contraindicated acutely). DiverticulOSIS is the painless bleeder. Never mix osis and itis.\n\nWhy not — Diverticulosis: DiverticulOSIS is the painless bleeder, not the painful febrile picture.  Angiodysplasia: Angiodysplasia bleeds painlessly; it doesn't cause fever.  Internal hemorrhoids: Hemorrhoids cause painless bright-red bleeding, not fever.  A colonic adenoma: An adenoma is usually asymptomatic.", "advanced"], ["Discontinuous skip lesions with cobblestoning on colonoscopy indicate:", ["Crohn disease", "Ulcerative colitis", "Ischemic colitis", "Pseudomembranous colitis", "Diverticular colitis"], 0, "Crohn disease is discontinuous (skip lesions) with cobblestoning and aphthous ulcers; the diagnosis is more visual than histologic. UC is continuous from the rectum.\n\nWhy not — Ulcerative colitis: Ulcerative colitis is CONTINUOUS from the rectum, without skip lesions.  Ischemic colitis: Ischemic colitis is segmental at watershed zones, not cobblestoned.  Pseudomembranous colitis: Pseudomembranous colitis shows yellow plaques (C. difficile).  Diverticular colitis: 'Diverticular colitis' is not the cobblestoning/skip pattern.", "basic"]]], [5, "Understand the indications and complications of endoscopy", [["The most dreaded complication of ERCP is:", ["Post-ERCP pancreatitis", "Esophageal perforation", "Aspiration pneumonia", "Splenic laceration", "Colonic perforation"], 0, "Manipulating the ampulla where the bile and pancreatic ducts meet can inflame the pancreas; post-ERCP pancreatitis is the dreaded complication, with an overall ~10% complication rate.\n\nWhy not — Esophageal perforation: Perforation is possible but not THE dreaded complication.  Aspiration pneumonia: Aspiration is a general anesthesia risk, not the signature ERCP complication.  Splenic laceration: Splenic injury is a colonoscopy-related rarity, not ERCP.  Colonic perforation: Colonic perforation is a colonoscopy complication, not ERCP.", "basic"]]], [6, "State the colonoscopy and the screening recommendations of the American College of Gastroenterology", [["Average-risk colorectal cancer screening should now begin at age:", ["45", "40", "50", "55", "60"], 0, "The 2022 update lowered the average-risk start age to 45 (from 50); African Americans now start at 45 as well.\n\nWhy not — 40: 40 is the high-risk/family-history start, not average-risk.  50: 50 was the OLD average-risk start, before 2022.  55: 55 is not a guideline start age.  60: 60 is far too late to begin average-risk screening.", "basic"], ["For average-risk colorectal cancer screening, the FIRST test that should be offered is:", ["Colonoscopy every 10 years", "Annual fecal immunochemical testing", "Cologuard every three years", "CT colonography every five years", "Flexible sigmoidoscopy every five years"], 0, "Colonoscopy q10y should be offered FIRST; a stool test (annual FIT) is offered only to patients who decline colonoscopy — not as an equivalent menu choice.\n\nWhy not — Annual fecal immunochemical testing: Annual FIT is first-tier but offered when colonoscopy is declined, not first.  Cologuard every three years: Cologuard is second-tier and not a first offer.  CT colonography every five years: CT colonography is a second-tier option.  Flexible sigmoidoscopy every five years: Flexible sigmoidoscopy is a limited second-tier option.", "basic"], ["Cologuard (FIT-DNA) is best described as a:", ["Cancer-detection test, not a prevention test", "Cancer-prevention test equal to colonoscopy", "First-tier test for high-risk patients", "Reliable test for advanced adenomas", "Replacement that needs no follow-up colonoscopy"], 0, "Cologuard is ~92% sensitive for cancer but only ~42% for advanced adenomas — so it detects cancer but doesn't prevent it (you can't remove a polyp through it). Every positive needs a colonoscopy.\n\nWhy not — Cancer-prevention test equal to colonoscopy: It is not equivalent to colonoscopy and does not prevent cancer.  First-tier test for high-risk patients: It is contraindicated in high-risk patients.  Reliable test for advanced adenomas: It misses ~58% of advanced adenomas — detection of polyps is only fair.  Replacement that needs no follow-up colonoscopy: Every positive Cologuard requires a follow-up colonoscopy.", "basic"], ["A 30-year-old's father had colon cancer at age 55. When and how often should screening colonoscopy be done?", ["Start at 40, every 5 years", "Start at 45, every 10 years", "Start at 50, every 10 years", "Start at 55, every 5 years", "Start at 45, every 5 years"], 0, "A first-degree relative with CRC under 60 makes this high-risk: colonoscopy every 5 years, starting at age 40 OR 10 years before the youngest affected relative (55 - 10 = 45), whichever is earlier — so 40.\n\nWhy not — Start at 45, every 10 years: q10y average-risk timing ignores the high-risk family history.  Start at 50, every 10 years: Start 50/q10y is the old average-risk rule, not high-risk.  Start at 55, every 5 years: 55 is too late; high-risk starts at 40 here.  Start at 45, every 5 years: Correct interval (q5y) but the start age should be 40, not 45.", "advanced"]]]]]];
// QUIZ_END
